{ Let's start again from this position and let's avoid to play Rb7+. White Rook in b5, instead of moving two ranks, it should move only one rank in b6. Move Rb6. In this way Black King cannot play Kg6 because the White Rook is protected by the second Rook. } { [%cal Rg6g8,Rg6a6,Rb5b8] }
3. Rbb6 { Black King is force to move in f8, e8, e7. Let's play Ke7. } { [%cal Gf7e7,Gf7e8,Gf7f8] } 3... Ke7 { White moves Rg7+. } 4. Rg7+ { Black King moves Kf8 hoping in a White blunder. } { [%cal Rb6h6,Rb6b8,Rg7g8] } 4... Kf8 { Again White mustn't move Rb8+. The best move here is Rb7 protecting the other Rook. Play Rb7. } 5. Rbb7 { Black King is force to move Ke8. } { [%cal Gf8e8,Rb7g7,Rb7b8,Rg7g8] } 5... Ke8 { White checkmate with Rb8# or Rg8#. Play Rb8#. } 6. Rb8# { Congratulations! Checkmate. Now you learned everything you need to know to correctly play 2 Rooks vs King End game. If you're the player with only the King, the only hope you have is to get close to one of the two Rooks and hope in an opponent's blunder. } *


